'''''Turunmaa''''' was a Finnish [[gunboat]] built in 1918. She served in the [[Finnish Navy]] during [[World War II]]. The ship was named after ''[[Turuma]]'', a type of frigate designed for use in shallow waters of the archipelago and served in the Swedish [[Archipelago fleet]] in the late 18th century. The frigates had in turn been named after [[Åboland|the region of Finland]].

During construction while in Russian lists (1916–1917) the ship had been named both ''Orlan'' and ''Tshirok''. ''Turunmaa'' was built in [[Helsinki]] for the [[Imperial Russian Navy]] but was taken over by Finnish troops in the [[Finnish Civil War]]. The ship was used as a training ship for Finnish sea cadets during peacetime and was nicknamed as ''Surunmaa'' (land of sorrow).{{sfnp|Auvinen|1983|p=34-35}}

==Interwar period==
In the second half of 1919, ''Turunmaa'', amongst other Finnish naval vessels, was tasked with security and patrol duties in the Koivisto region where the British naval detachment was located.{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968a|p=106}} On 4 September 1939, ''Turunmaa'' as part of the Coastal Fleet was moved to the Sea of Åland.{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968a|p=224-225}} However, for the rest of the autumn, ''Turunmaa'' patrolled the waters from Kotka to Koivisto together with ''Karjala''.{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968a|p=236}}

==Winter War==
{{main|Naval warfare in the Winter War}}
On 1 December 1939 ''Turunmaa'' was covering the minelaying effort by auxiliary minelayer Suomi south-east of [[Krepost Sveaborg#Isosaari|Isosaari]].{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968a|p=262}} ''Turunmaa'' join to the Coastal Fleet near Åland in mid December 1939. She participated in anti-submarine patrols which continued until the sea froze on 30 January.{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968a|p=257,261}}

==Continuation War==
{{main|Baltic Sea campaigns (1939–1945)}}

''Turunmaa'' was tasked with escort duties at the start of the Continuation War. She was detached from that duty following the Soviet [[Battle of Bengtskär|attack to Bengtskär]] and ordered to rejoin the rest of the Finnish gunboats. On 29 August ''Turunmaa'' together with {{ship|Finnish gunboat|Karjala||2}}, {{ship|Finnish gunboat|Hämeenmaa||2}} and {{ship|Finnish gunboat|Uusimaa||2}} escorted by {{ship|Finnish minelayer|Riilahti||2}} and {{ship|Finnish minelayer|Ruotsinsalmi||2}} sailed through the main Soviet minebarrier south of [[Hanko]] to the eastern Gulf of Finland.{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968b|p=34,42-43}}

After island of [[Sommers]] had been thought to be unmanned following the shelling of the island by {{ship|Finnish patrol gunboat|VTV-1||2}} on 9 October 1941 Finns prepared to occupy it. ''Turunmaa'' was escorting the landing force in its failed attempt to land on 11 October as the landing force turned back before reaching the shore when Soviets opened fire. On 29 October ''Turunmaa'' together with ''Karjala'' shelled the island.{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968b|p=56}}

On 1942 ''Turunmaa'' like other Finnish gunboats was tasked with guarding of the minebarriers northeast of [[Hogland]] and performing anti-submarine patrols in the same region. On 8 August ''Turunmaa'' was sortied to fend off the Soviet [[Battle of Someri|attack on Someri]] but arrived several hours after ''Hämeenmaa'' and ''Uusimaa''. ''Turunmaa'' shelled both the nearby Soviet vessels as well as positions of the Soviet landing force on the island. After the naval action had already ended ''Turunmaa'' was slightly damaged by a near-miss by a bomb and suffered some crew losses (2 dead, 8 wounded) as overheated barrels of both of the 20mm Madsen guns aboard exploded.{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968b|p=86,105-109}}

On 2 May 1943 while guarding the mine barriers northeast of Hogland, ''Turunmaa'' was seriously damaged in an air raid and the sinking ship had to be beached to shallow water at Haapasaaret (group of islands south from [[Kotka]]). Crew casualties were 1 dead and 9 wounded. The ship was immediately refloated and was fully repaired by 23 October 1943.{{sfnp|Auvinen|1983|p=34-35}}{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968b|loc= Supplement I}}

When [[Vyborg–Petrozavodsk Offensive|Soviet summer offensive of 1944]] started ''Turunmaa'' was first part of the flotilla evacuating the Koivisto region. And later took part in the [[Battle of Vyborg Bay (1944)|fighting at Bay of Viborg]] on 4 July 1944 as part of the Battle Group Arho consisting of Finnish and German light naval units. While defending against repeated air attacks and attacks by motor torpedo boats two bombs exploded under the boilerroom of ''Turunmaa''. ''Turunmaa'' started leaking and the aft gun was jammed and the ship was temporarily unable to participate to the action. This and other damages to the ships of the Battle Group Arho led to its withdrawal from action.{{sfnp|Kijanen|1968b|p=160,173-175}}

